A while ago I asked what other packages I should optomize for Pentium. One=20
person answered GlibC. This got me thinking about GCC itself, so I asked on=20
another list and got a few answers, most were "don't even think about it" but=
=20
a few suggested GCC and one pointed me to Linux From Scratch.After having a g=
ood search around the lfs site, I've decided I'm going to=20
give it a whirl. I've got a spare box and loads of free time, so why not ;-)T=
he lfs site, however warns NOT to use optimizations when compiling GCC or=20
GlibC? A quick google found PGCC, a Pentium optimizing patch for GCC, but the=
=20
site does not seem to have been updated in quite some time?So, my general pla=
n, and I'm taking my time with this:Partition the hard drive for the lfs set-=
up with 4 partitions, /, /usr, /var=20
and /home.
Install a base Debian system into the /home  partition so I can build the=20
rest of the system into the other partitions.
Using Debian, build the initial packages into the / and /usr partitions. I'll=
=20
try to optimize GCC and GlibC in this first stage.
chroot to the / partition and re-build the base packages for shared libs.
strip de-bugging from the binaries and change the boot so the system boot=20
from / rather than /home, then move /home to it's proper partition.All going =
well, I should now have a full base Linux system running that is=20
fully optimized for my PentiumMMX including GCC and GlibC.Now I can build zli=
b and then X, again optimizing. And I can follow this with=20
the various graphics libs, qt lib and finally KDE.If all goes well, I will pr=
obably repeate this for my Dual system, once I can=20
find a match for the slot1 550Mhz PIII Iv'e got.I might even be tempted to wr=
ite this up for the site.Cheers,	John Gay--=20
